{{Infobox recurring event | name = Djakarta Warehouse Project | logo = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | logo_size = | image =Garuda Bot at DWP 2017.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Garuda Land, the main stage of Djakarta Warehouse Project. | status = Active | genre = Music festival | frequency = Annually | location =[[Garuda Wisnu Kencana Cultural Park]] | coordinates = | years_active = | first = 2008 | founder_name = | last = {{start date|2017|12|15|df=y}} – {{end date|2017|12|16|df=y}} | next = | participants = | attendance = 90,000 (2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7880873/djakarta-worldwide-2017-lineup|title=Djakarta Warehouse Project 2017 Announces Flume, Tiesto, Marshmello in Phase 1 Lineup|newspaper=Billboard|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> | capacity = | area = | budget = | activity = | leader_name = | patron = | organised = Ismaya Live | filing = | people = | member = | sponsor = | website = {{URL|http://www.djakartawarehouse.com/}} | footnotes = }} '''Djakarta Warehouse Project''' or '''DWP''' is a dance music festival held in [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8470156/djakarta-warehouse-project-2018-lineup|title=The Weeknd, DJ Snake, Major Lazer and More Announced For Djakarta Warehouse Project 2018|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=Billboard|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> It is one of the largest annual dance music festivals in Asia, featuring dance music artists from around the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mixmag.asia/read/djakarta-warehouse-project-becomes-asias-largest-music-festival-after-drawing-90-000-local|title=DJAKARTA WAREHOUSE PROJECT BECOMES ASIA’S LARGEST 2-DAY DANCE MUSIC FESTIVAL WITH 90,000|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=Mix Mag|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>
==History== The festival originated from a nightclub event in 2008 called Blowfish Warehouse Project at Jakarta’s renowned night club Blowfish. Featuring 3 arenas within the club’s vicinity, the festival’s first edition boasted more than 5.000 audience. The second edition of the festival was planned to be held on 24 April 2010. However, a fight broke out three weeks before the planned date of the festival, damaging parts of the venue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.detik.com/news/berita/1331621/bentrokan-di-blowfish-buntut-peristiwa-sabtu-malam|title=Bentrokan di Blowfish Buntut Peristiwa Sabtu Malam|work=detiknews|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> Organisers moved the festival to Pantai Carnaval in Ancol and rebranded the festival with a new name, Djakarta Warehouse Project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.scmp.com/culture/music/article/2112901/largest-edm-festival-asia-how-indonesias-djakarta-warehouse-project|title=How an Indonesian EDM festival became Asia’s largest rave|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref>
