{{for|the genus of fungi|Gibellina (fungus)}} {{Infobox Italian comune | name = Gibellina | official_name = Comune di Gibellina | native_name = | image_skyline =Panorama di Gibellina Nuova.JPG | imagesize = | image_alt = | image_caption = | image_shield = Gibellina-Stemma.png | shield_alt = | image_map = | map_alt = | map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|37|49|N|12|52|E|display=inline}} | coordinates_footnotes = | region = [[Sicily]] | province = [[Province of Trapani|Trapani]] (TP) | frazioni = | mayor_party = | mayor = Salvatore Sutera | area_footnotes = | area_total_km2 = 46.57 | population_footnotes = | population_total = 4028 | population_as_of = 28 February 2017 | pop_density_footnotes = | population_demonym = Gibellinesi | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 233 | twin1 = | twin1_country = | saint = [[Roch|Saint Roch]] | day = 16 August | postal_code = 91024 | area_code = 0924 | website = {{official website|http://www.gibellina.gov.it}} | footnotes = }}
'''Gibellina''' ([[Sicilian language|Sicilian]]: ''Gibbiddina'') is a small city and ''[[comune]]'' in the [[Province of Trapani]], the mountains of central [[Sicily]], [[Italy]]. It was destroyed by the [[1968 Belice earthquake]].<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,837724,00.html The Day the Earth Shook], Time Magazine, January 26, 1968</ref>
The new city, Gibellina Nuova, was rebuilt some {{convert|11|km|mi|0}} distant from the old one. The new city was designed by many of the most prominent artists and architects in Italy, but done in a piecemeal fashion so that the parts of the new city bear little relation to one another or to the indigenous architecture of Sicily.
'''Ruderi di Gibellina''' (as the ruins of the city are now referred to) remained just as it was after the earthquake, practically a ghost-town. Artist [[Alberto Burri]] covered the entirety of the ruins in concrete, while preserving the streetscape. Additionally, Italian sculptor [[Pietro Consagra]] and Senator [[Ludovico Corrao]] formed an open-air museum with a Consagra sculpture "Porta del Belice" or "Door to Belice" at the entrance. Consagra expressed a wish to be buried at Gibellina on his deathbed in July 2005.<ref>[http://www.agi.it/english/news.pl?doc=200507161738-1121-RT1-CRO-0-NF11&page=0&id=agionline-eng.oggitalia Agenzia Giornalistica Italia news story on death and burial of Consagra]</ref>
[[File:Ruderi di Gibellina.jpg|thumb|600px|left|Ruderi di Gibellina by Gabriel Valentini.]]
